<HEADLINE>
<P>
36 OF IRAQ'S 55 EMBASSY STAFFERS EXPELLED BY U.S. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JIM MANN, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Bush Administration on Monday expelled two-thirds of the Iraqi diplomatic 
staff in Washington and encouraged 34 other nations with embassies in Kuwait to 
take similar steps against Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
In Kuwait and Iraq, meanwhile, Iraqi military authorities intensified efforts 
to round up foreigners. State Department officials said that over the weekend, 
seven more private American citizens were taken into Iraqi custody. 
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Embassy in Kuwait city is now operating only with its own water and 
food supplies, which State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said are 
sufficient for U.S. diplomats to hold out "at least several days" against the 
siege by Iraqi troops. The embassy has been operating with its own electricity 
generator since troops cut off its supplies, water and power from outside. 
</P>
<P>
President Bush told a news conference in Maine that the United States is 
requiring Iraqi diplomats to leave the country by Thursday, and he contrasted 
that order with Iraq's policy of preventing American diplomats from leaving. 
</P>
<P>
"Nobody will be held against their will," Bush said of the Iraqi diplomats. 
"They're all free to leave." 
</P>
<P>
The State Department spokeswoman said the expulsions were in response to Iraq's 
recent violations of international law, including its efforts to annex Kuwait 
and, "in particular, the illegal order to close our embassy in Kuwait." 
</P>
<P>
Until now, Iraq has been allowed to maintain 55 of its nationals -- including 
both diplomats and non-diplomatic staff members -- at its embassy in 
Washington. The order Monday requires Iraq to cut its embassy back to 19 
people. 
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials acknowledged they chose the figure of 19 because it matches the 
total number of American diplomats still working in Iraq and Kuwait. About 55 
other American diplomats who had been working out of the U.S. Embassy in Kuwait 
left that nation with the intention of leaving the region but were barred by 
Iraqi officials from leaving Baghdad. 
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials hinted broadly that if more American diplomats are forced out of 
the U.S. embassies in Kuwait and Iraq, more Iraqis will be expelled from 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
The President told reporters that the United States is "trying to keep a 
reasonable parallel in terms of numbers." 
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Mashat, the Iraqi ambassador to Washington, told reporters that the 
U.S. decision to expel most of his staff was "uncalled for, unfair and unjust. 
We feel we have been victimized once more." Mashat said the U.S. action will 
reduce the effectiveness of Iraqi diplomats in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
The U.S. order requires seven diplomats and 29 non-diplomatic staff members at 
Iraq's embassy to pack up and leave the United States within 72 hours -- or by 
4:30 p.m. Thursday. Included in the order is the embassy's entire commercial 
section, which is responsible for promoting Iraq's trade with the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
"We don't feel there's much need for the Iraqis to be here trying to buy at 
this particular time," Tutwiler told a State Department briefing. 
</P>
<P>
In addition, the State Department imposed a series of new restrictions on the 
remaining Iraqi personnel at the embassy. 
</P>
<P>
They will be prohibited from traveling more than 25 miles from Washington, and 
they and their families will be given only single-entry visas to the United 
States instead of the customary multiple-entry visas that allow them to enter 
and leave the country virtually at will. 
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Tutwiler said, use of Iraqi Embassy funds for Iraqi students and 
for other humanitarian needs will be "closely controlled." She did not explain 
what this last restriction will mean. 
</P>
<P>
The new restrictions do not apply to Iraq's United Nations mission in New York, 
which will be allowed to continue operating at full strength. 
</P>
<P>
On Sunday night, Deputy Assistant Secretary of State David Mack called in 
representatives of the 34 countries to tell them about the new U.S. move 
against Iraqi diplomats. Those nations have refused to close their embassies in 
Kuwait despite threats from Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
"The United States is urging other governments, particularly those whose 
embassies have been affected by Iraqi actions in Kuwait, to consider taking 
similar actions against Iraq's official and non-official presence in their 
countries," Tutwiler explained. 
</P>
<P>
Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence S. Eagleburger summoned Mashat, the Iraqi 
ambassador, to the State Department at 9 a.m. Monday to inform him of the 
expulsion order. Mashat himself was not covered by the order and will be 
permitted to remain here. 
</P>
<P>
"I was surprised when I was informed of this action," Mashat said later. " . . 
. We will try to be cooperative with the United States, because we have nothing 
against the American people." 
</P>
<P>
State Department officials said Monday that over the weekend, two private 
Americans in Kuwait were taken from their apartments by Iraqi soldiers. "Once 
again, the Iraqis knocked on the door, and when the two answered they were 
taken to the Regency Hotel in Kuwait city," said Tutwiler. 
</P>
<P>
Four other Americans also were picked up in Kuwait on Saturday and brought to 
the same hotel, where they and the others were held by Iraqi authorities. State 
Department officials said they did not know how the four had been captured. 
</P>
<P>
In addition, one private American in Iraq was taken away from his place of 
work. U.S. officials did not know where this American was taken. 
</P>
<P>
In all, State Department officials say, Iraqi authorities have rounded up 42 
Americans inside Iraq and another 21 in Kuwait. They are the only Americans 
under direct Iraqi detention or control, out of the total of about 3,000 
Americans who were barred from leaving Iraq and Kuwait. 
</P>
<P>
"In Kuwait, food availability appears adequate, although stocks of some items, 
especially fruits and vegetables, are not plentiful," Tutwiler said Monday. "In 
Iraq, we know that internal food prices are going through the roof for certain 
commodities like rice and sugar, and we know that there are bread lines in 
Iraq." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
DIPLOMATS AT EMBASSIES IN KUWAIT 
</P>
<P>
Many countries have refused to bow to Iraq's demands to pull their embassies 
out of Kuwait and move their diplomats to Baghdad. Here is the status of envoys 
at the embassies of a number of key countries: 
</P>
<P>
Country: United States 
</P>
<P>
Status: Defied order to close; embassy surrounded. Ambassador W. Nathaniel 
Howell remains insidewith staff of nine. 
</P>
<P>
Country: Soviet Union 
</P>
<P>
Status: Moscow said all Soviet citizens in Kuwait including diplomats had left, 
leaving the embassy empty. But this did not mean the Kremlin had ended Soviet 
representation. 
</P>
<P>
Country: Britain 
</P>
<P>
Status: Defied order to close; embassy reported surrounded. Four diplomats 
inside, including Ambassador Michael Weston and Consul Larry Banks. 
</P>
<P>
Country: Belgium 
</P>
<P>
Status: Ambassador Marcel van Roey and a first secretary staff the embassy. 
</P>
<P>
Country: Denmark 
</P>
<P>
Status: Ambassador Birger Dan Nielsen told not to leave embassy voluntarily but 
what this means has been left to his discretion, according to the Foreign 
Ministry. 
</P>
<P>
Country: France 
</P>
<P>
Status: Six diplomats still in Kuwait, led by Charge d'Affaires Jean-Pierre 
Galtier. 
</P>
<P>
Country: Greece 
</P>
<P>
Status: Charge d'Affaires Dimitris Zavoritis remains with a staff of four 
Greeks and three Kuwaitis. 
</P>
<P>
Country: Italy 
</P>
<P>
Status: Ambassador Marco Colombo remains with his second Secretary. 
</P>
<P>
Country: Netherlands 
</P>
<P>
Status: Four diplomats and four dependents remain, led by Ambassador Joop 
Veling. 
</P>
<P>
Country: Spain 
</P>
<P>
Status: Trade attache Juan Jose Buitrago is in charge of the embassy. 
(Ambassador Juan Jose Arboli was in Spain at time of the invasion and was 
refused permission to return.) 
</P>
<P>
Country: West Germany 
</P>
<P>
Status: Ambassador Claus Soenksen remains in the mission. Bonn refused to say 
how many diplomats are inside. 
</P>
<P>
Country: Egypt 
</P>
<P>
Status: Embassy functioning with staff of 20, including Ambassador Saeed 
Rifaat. 
</P>
<P>
Country: Bahrain 
</P>
<P>
Status: Bahrain refuses to close mission. The ambassador and another diplomat 
remain in Kuwait. 
</P>
<P>
Country: Morocco 
</P>
<P>
Status: Said its diplomats would stay. 
</P>
<P>
Country: Japan 
</P>
<P>
Status: Defied orders to close embassy; not clear how many diplomats are left. 
</P>
<P>
Country: Iran 
</P>
<P>
Status: Embassy open. 
</P>
<P>
Country: Canada 
</P>
<P>
Status: Bolstered staff with diplomat from Baghdad, for total of six. 
</P>
<P>
Country: Bangladesh 
</P>
<P>
Status: Ambassador Shahabuddin Ahmad believed to have remained with four 
diplomats. 
</P>
<P>
Country: Czechoslovakia 
</P>
<P>
Status: Ambassador Strakos was ordered to stay put unless threatened with 
violence. Accompanied by one other diplomat. 
</P>
<P>
Country: East Germany 
</P>
<P>
Status: Ambassador Kurt Merkel and his wife remain with orders to keep the 
mission open. 
</P>
<P>
Country: Poland 
</P>
<P>
Status: The embassy will stay open. Charge d'Affaires Jan Dworak leads the 
mission with three officials of State Trade Office. 
</P>
<P>
Country: Sweden 
</P>
<P>
Status: Two diplomats still in Kuwait, including Ambassador Ingolf Kiesow. 
</P>
<P>
Country: Norway 
</P>
<P>
Status: Ambassador Hans Wilhelm Longva, two other envoys remain in embassy. 
</P>
<P>
Country: Switzerland 
</P>
<P>
Status: Charge d'Affaires Franco Besomi and one other diplomat still in place. 
</P>
<P>
Country: Thailand 
</P>
<P>
Status: Three embassy officials still in Kuwait, headed by Charge d'Affaires 
Atsiphol Chabchitchaidol. 
</P>
<P>
Source: Reuters 
</P>
</TEXT>
