<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WEEK AHEAD: DURBAN; 
</P>
<P>
A PIVOTAL PARTY CONGRESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
South Africa's ruling National Party, battling to hold onto white voters 
nervous about apartheid reforms, meets in this southeastern coastal city 
Thursday and Friday for its first provincial congress since President Frederik 
W. de Klerk's election 11 months ago. 
</P>
<P>
Its biggest problem is retaining white support long enough to prove that the 
reform process can bring the country together and end its international 
ostracism. But recent black factional fighting near Johannesburg has fueled 
white fears of a future black-led government. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, party leaders have hinted that they may also discuss opening their 
membership rolls to all races. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
SOUTH AFRICA -- POLITICS; NATIONAL PARTY (SOUTH AFRICA); CONFERENCES; POLITICAL 
PLATFORMS 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
