<HEADLINE>
<P>
SKY DIVER HURT IN JUMP AS CHUTE OPENS IN PLANE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
HAZLETON, Pa. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A sky diver whose parachute inadvertently opened inside a plane was forced to 
leap when only 800 feet off the ground but landed in a clump of trees and 
survived. 
</P>
<P>
He was listed in guarded condition at a hospital, apparently with back 
injuries. 
</P>
<P>
The chute had caught on the plane's door, opened and was sucked outside. "He 
had to jump out. Otherwise he would have been pulled through the wall of the 
airplane," a witness said. He said sky divers typically prefer jumps from 5,000 
to 10,000 feet. 
</P>
<P>
Drag from the partly opened chute helped break the man's fall Sunday and may 
have saved his life, a companion said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
