<P>
THE BIG APPLE IS A BIG BITE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Big Apple may be a nice place to visit, but have your wallet handy -- at 
$282 per day, it's the sixth most expensive in the world and far outranks 
domestic competition, a survey said today. 
</P>
<P>
The closest domestic competitor for the dubious honor was Washington, where a 
one-day visit for business travelers averaged $216, according to a survey of 55 
cities prepared by Runzheimer International for Traveler magazine. 
</P>
<P>
A day in town, for the purposes of the survey, meant three meals a day and a 
single room at the standard rate in a first-class hotel. 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles was ranked sixth in the survey, at $183 per day, with San Francisco 
seventh at $172. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
