</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE'S PHARMACY: ANTIVIRAL DRUG CAN EASE HERPES PAIN, AVERT LESIONS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOE GRAEDON and DR. TERESA GRAEDON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: When we got married 20 years ago, I had herpes. We were careful, but 
10 years later my husband caught it. 
</P>
<P>
My case has gradually improved to the point that I now have an outbreak only 
every other year. But my husband suffers terribly with an episode at least once 
a month. 
</P>
<P>
Before he came down with genital herpes, we were extremely happy. Since then, 
he has not touched me -- no kiss, no hug, no tender word. He has abandoned me 
emotionally, spiritually, financially and physically. We have separate bedrooms 
and bank accounts. 
</P>
<P>
Herpes has been an unbelievable evil in our lives. Is there any hope for a 
cure? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: Although it is unfair, your husband seems to be blaming you for his 
misery. Unfortunately, there is still no cure for herpes, but it may be 
possible for him to control his outbreaks. 
</P>
<P>
Zovirax (acyclovir) is an effective antiviral medication that can prevent 
lesions when it is taken on a daily basis. These prescription pills have 
revolutionized the treatment of genital herpes. They can also speed healing of 
cold sores or fever blisters caused by herpes 1. 
</P>
<P>
Your husband should discuss his problem with a dermatologist or urologist. In 
addition, both of you would perhaps benefit from marital counseling to help 
overcome the years of bitterness caused by a viral infection. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Q. Both my daughter and I have had problems with malodorous perspiration. The 
odor is very difficult to launder out of clothing. 
</P>
<P>
We found the solution in Prevention magazine, and want to pass it along. Zinc 
gluconate, 20 mg., prevents smelly perspiration for us. Perhaps others will 
benefit as well. 
</P>
<P>
A. In Germany, zinc compounds are included in deodorants to prevent unpleasant 
smells from sweat. We have been unable to locate any scientific studies 
verifying that oral zinc supplements can have this effect. However, the dose of 
zinc that you are taking is within a safe range, and as far as we know, is not 
likely to cause any complications. 
</P>
<P>
Foods that are rich in this mineral include whole grains, especially wheat 
germ, seafood, brewer's yeast and meat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
